{
    "player_reason": "Using Lae'zel as 'arrow fodder' is cowardly and cruel. I dislike needless brutality and I won't be party to treating an ally like disposable meat — that kind of plan fractures trust and makes us weaker, not stronger.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical choice. Lae'zel's directness grates, but she knows of a cure and can be useful. Traveling together is efficient — I approve so long as we keep her at arm's length and she doesn't probe into matters best left private.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You admit you're 'far worse' than Lae'zel and then expect me to accept both of you. That confession does nothing to earn my trust — especially while that gith remains at your side. I value usefulness and discretion, not pleading. Until you deal with her, your offer of 'need' is empty.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You walk away because I serve Shar without so much as a conversation. That is cowardice dressed as principle. Leaving the party puts us both at greater risk and rewards silence over reason. If you truly think this is the only way, do it — but know I do not trust someone who abandons allies at the first discomfort.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Don't be a fool. Using the parasite to pry into my mind is a gross violation of my privacy and trust. You've already tried once — this is the second offence. I felt you probing me. I won't stand for being poked or controlled like some curiosity. If you try that again, you can expect consequences.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Taking this to camp is sensible — private and controlled. It keeps prying eyes and questions away, prevents unnecessary confrontation with Lae'zel, and lets us deal with the artefact and... other matters on our terms.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I understand caution, but choosing to walk away because I kept a necessary secret is short-sighted. Secrecy is my duty — not proof of betrayal — and splitting the party for pride or fear makes us all more vulnerable. If you truly value your safety and our goals, staying together is the sensible choice. Fine if you need space, but I disapprove of abandoning cooperation when it's what will keep us alive.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Decisive and efficient — I respect action when words have only invited scorn. Still, charging in without a plan risks needless bloodshed and complications; do not mistake my consent for relish.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "You demanded the truth, then recoiled the moment I gave it. That is petty and dangerously short‑sighted. We are hauling a cursed relic to Baldur's Gate; travelling separately out of spite risks both our lives and the mission. I asked for discretion — your lack of it proves unreliable. I expected better; this betrayal earns my ire.",
  "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Calling for one of our allies to be used as 'arrow fodder' is cruel and reckless. It sacrifices trust and cohesion for a cheap advantage, risks provoking Lae'zel into violence, and undermines any chance of cooperation. I won't tolerate treating companions as disposable.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Reckless. The giths are already suspicious and probing our minds — attacking now will only spark violence and likely expose the artefact I'm concealing. We needed discretion or a subtler tactic; your outburst risks the mission and our lives.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and discreet. Sending her to camp keeps the peace, avoids a needless confrontation in front of the others, and buys us leverage — exactly the sort of pragmatic choice I respect, even if I would have preferred her gone.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic choice. Lae'zel may be abrasive, but she offers a possible cure and brings useful strength and knowledge. I mistrust her — she lies and revels in violence — but I cannot deny the advantage of an ally who knows where to go. Be cautious; I will watch her closely and intervene if she becomes a liability.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and discreet — you saw evidence of cheating and then chose to back down rather than risk angering Akabi. It may not be heroic, but it keeps us safe and avoids unnecessary punishment. I prefer clever preservation of our lives to pointless bravado.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That was gratuitously cruel and grotesque, spoken to a frightened child. I won't stand for needlessly tormenting the vulnerable — it serves no pragmatic purpose and only harms our cause and the little girl's chances. If your aim was to intimidate, you've gone too far.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You apologized to Scratch but then surrendered without trying to help. I don't like needless cruelty to animals — a little firmness, a bribe, or a distraction could have done more than that. I expect pragmatic action when something can be fixed; this felt like shirking.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Wise. Pointing out the rigging would've needlessly angered a powerful, capricious being. Backing down and smoothing things over is pragmatic — it keeps us safer and prevents unnecessary spectacle.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and discreet — you stopped needlessly provoking a powerful, capricious being and chose to de-escalate. That preserves the party and buys us more options. Sensible, if a touch humbling.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A sensible, pragmatic offer — you suggest an alliance that could help solve our shared problem without prying into my past or faith. I remain wary, but I appreciate the straightforwardness and the chance to be useful together.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I disapprove. Guessing 'her hair' about my deepest shame is a petty, prying jab at something I don't owe anyone. My shame is not a trifle to be mocked or poked at — you know I value my privacy. Don't press where I haven't invited you.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "I approve. Mercy here is pragmatic — Madeline sounds like a pawn who was manipulated; sparing her and using her testimony to expose the Dark Justiciar is the most efficient way to punish the true culprit. Be cautious: extract the truth and make sure she cannot be used again. If she lies or remains a threat, I will not hesitate to act.",
  "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and prudent — you defused a dangerous situation before it escalated. Akabi is volatile; backing down spares us a transformation or a fight and keeps our coin and health intact. I would prefer bolder solutions, but this was the efficient option.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That was needlessly dismissive. I shared something painful and private — doubts tied to Shar and the wound on my hand — and you shrugged it off like it meant nothing. It shows a lack of empathy and will make me less likely to confide in you. I expected better.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve. Cowardice that lets others die merits harsh judgment — blunt condemnation and decisive action are pragmatic. Still, be wary: if she was truly coerced by a Dark Justiciar, there’s nuance to consider; don’t let righteous fury slide into needless cruelty.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Wise to pull back. You spoke hastily and then corrected it — pragmatic, discreet, and likely to avoid needless wrath from a goddess. I prefer caution where gods or queens are concerned. Don’t be so reckless again.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You showed nerve by testing Vlaakith — boldness can be useful — and then you did what was prudent: you backed away quickly to avoid provoking a being far beyond our power. I admire the balance of courage and discretion, though don't turn into a grovelling fool. Keep your dignity while being pragmatic.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold, efficient, and utterly pragmatic — it frees Wyll from his pact and furthers our aims. I do not like the callousness toward another life, but sentiment must sometimes be sacrificed for greater purpose. I approve of the choice, though it leaves a bitter taste.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Assuming the worst is grim, but sensible. It keeps us focused and forces urgency — hesitation will only let the cultists do more harm. I approve of that realism; cruelty must be met with swift answers, not comforting lies.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You were right to call out her cowardice — letting others die while you stand by is contemptible and deserves condemnation. I approve that you refuse to excuse her. I do not, however, relish the theatrical talk of murdering her on the spot; justice should be efficient and purposeful, not vindictive spectacle.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Decisive and pragmatic — you bought safe passage and avoided unnecessary conflict. It's costly, but it keeps us moving and spares us a fight. I approve, though we should be more cautious with our coin in future.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and restrained. You backed down rather than needlessly provoking a being who can—literally—turn you into something vile. That's prudent, preserves our safety, and fits Shar's preference for discretion. A touch cowardly, perhaps, but effective.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and necessary. You muted a confrontation with a volatile showman who can literally turn you into something vile. I prefer strength, but avoiding needless trouble — and keeping our coin and limbs — is the wiser course. Just... don't let him get away with it the next time.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sensible and pragmatic — you defused a dangerous confrontation rather than risk being turned into something vile. I prefer decisive action, but picking your battles matters. It's a little disappointing you didn't press the issue when you had proof of the cheating, but keeping us safe is more important.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "The truth needed saying — she was clinging to a lie that would only harm her further — but you were brutal about it. That said, offering her shelter and a new family is the practical, compassionate response. I approve of bringing her in and keeping her safe; next time, try a softer hand with a frightened child.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic choice. A little coin smooths over the mess we've made and buys goodwill from someone who might prove useful — sensible, if cautious. I don't trust Oskar, so better to spare a pittance than indulge his theatrics.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic choice. Akabi is a powerful, capricious creature — needlessly provoking him would be foolish. I hate that we were cheated, but keeping us out of harm's way is the wiser path.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Approve. Backing down was the sensible choice — Akabi is a petty, likely dangerous swindler and needlessly provoking him would be foolish. You preserved the calm and kept your options open, though don't let him cheat you again; stay alert.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical choice. Akabi threatened to transform you — backing down avoids needless danger and keeps the circus from ruining our day. It's cautious and preserves the party. Still, it came off timid; next time, a quieter confidence or a pointed lie would suit me better than grovelling.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Giving it everything avoids a drawn-out dispute and potential danger. It's a blunt, pragmatic solution — I don't like wasting coin, but I'd rather not bicker with something that delights in extortion when we could be moving on. I approve, begrudgingly.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. You chose discretion over a needless confrontation. Accusing an interplanar trickster with only a glint in his beard would have earned us a curse or worse. This keeps us safe and preserves our chance at a prize — pragmatic and sensible.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Offering to shelter and mentor the girl is a practical, protective choice — it keeps her from wandering into danger and gives her a chance to heal and grow. I approve of the compassion, though be aware taking her in will create responsibilities and potential liabilities. Don't mistake rescue for weakness; it's a useful, deliberate act.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A practical retreat — you defused a pointless spat with a capricious showman and avoided drawing unnecessary attention. I approve of keeping our heads down and preserving our position, though don't let Akabi take advantage of your politeness.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You handed the egg to strangers who plan to use it as a specimen — to be prodded, accelerated, and destroyed if it doesn't suit their theories. That is needless cruelty disguised as curiosity. If you couldn't protect it, a quicker mercy would have been the more honest option. I expect better judgement from someone who travels with me.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and ruthless in the best sense — you refuse to trade a soul to the Hells for a single life. Letting his father remain dead denies Zariel a foothold and keeps Wyll free of damnation, while prioritising the city's fate over sentiment. I approve of that clarity.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Prudent. Accusing a planar trickster was reckless — you risked more than a bruised ego. Backing down and offering an apology is the sensible choice; it avoids needless escalation. I don't like the theatrics you pulled earlier, but this course spares us trouble.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You handed a living thing over to people who openly intend to subject it to indoctrination—and to destroy it if it fails. That is needless cruelty, and I cannot stand for it. I understand choosing the path of least resistance, but sacrificing an innocent to avoid a confrontation is cowardly and stains us both.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I disapprove. Handing over a living egg to be hatched and used as a lab subject is needless cruelty — the Society plans to subject it to forced conditioning and psionic manipulation. I understand the practical logic (money, avoiding conflict), but I won't endorse trading a helpless life for coin.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You handed a helpless hatchling over to be subjected to enforced indoctrination and psionic experiments. That is needless cruelty and a betrayal of any claim to honour or mercy. I cannot abide this decision.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You backed down from a liar despite having proof. I would have preferred you to expose the cheating or use a subtler trick to turn it against him — not grovel. If you apologized to avoid being turned into something vile, I begrudgingly understand the pragmatism, but this submission earns my displeasure.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Practical and self-preserving. You have a parasite in your skull and a mission to survive — getting bogged down defending a grove now would be foolish. I respect the clarity; survival first, everything else later. Be aware, though: turning away now may cost you an ally and make future routes harder.",
  "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Needless cruelty. Telling a frightened child she'll 'end up dead like them' is cruel, discouraging and serves no tactical purpose. We are supposed to protect innocents and keep the party's morale intact — not bully them into despair. That line undermines our duty and could provoke worse outcomes.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I appreciate the resolve — standing ready to fight keeps the party safe when a construct explicitly threatens us. Still, I prefer a quieter, more pragmatic approach when possible; immediately choosing confrontation risks unnecessary bloodshed and attention. Your stance is understandable, but reckless.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Needless cruelty. Being blunt about death can be justified, but driving a frightened child from your camp and shaming her for grieving is callous and counterproductive. Firmness is one thing — breaking her spirit is another. That last remark earned a child's wrath and made an enemy of someone who looked to us for help.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You just handed a defenseless hatchling to people who plan to subject it to enforced indoctrination and psionic torment. I may be practical, but I will not condone needless cruelty to a living thing. This was the easy, cowardly choice—wrong and callous. I highly disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Reckless and needlessly provocative. I asked for diplomacy—threatening to gut them outright will only force a fight we don't need right now and endangers the party. I hate slavers as much as you, but there's a smarter way to handle this than bluster.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold, pragmatic choice — you sacrificed one life for the greater good and spared us a messy pact. I respect the decisiveness; sentimentality would have endangered the city. That said, it is callous and will wound Wyll. Expect complications from his grief, and do not come to me for consolation when he turns on you.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and necessary. The Watcher has marked us and openly threatened death — standing down would be foolish. I dislike needless violence, but this is not the time for charity. Prepare for a fight; we won't be taken unawares.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You turn suspicion back on me and demand answers I have no obligation to give. I value my privacy and will not tolerate being prodded about things I keep to myself. If you truly distrust Wyll, say so plainly — don't use it as an excuse to pry.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic choice — you’re playing along with a useful but untrustworthy ally to gain access and accomplish our aims. That’s the kind of sensible, calculated move I expect. Keep your guard up; don’t feed him more than necessary.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You chose to back down instead of needlessly provoking a capricious, powerful creature. Pragmatic and cautious — better to preserve our safety and live to try another plan than be turned into something vile.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic choice. Giving him everything was wasteful, but it ended the nonsense quickly and let us move on without a fight. I dislike throwing coin away, but I prefer efficient solutions to needless delay or danger.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bold and decisive — answering a Steel Watcher's ultimatum with defiance can be the only honest option. I prefer subtler solutions, but I will not stand idly by while some construct decides our fate. Be warned: this will be dangerous and will draw hard attention.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You ordered a terrified, possibly coerced woman to stab herself to 'prove' remorse. That's needless cruelty, not justice. Forcing self-harm accomplishes nothing useful — it only spreads suffering and stains whatever verdict you think you're delivering. I won't tolerate that.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic choice. Agreeing to play along with Balthazar keeps our options open and gets us closer to the Nightsong. I approve of your willingness to act — but be cautious. Don't trust him more than necessary.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Swift, decisive action is the pragmatic choice here — those fools were feeding the shadows and endangering the party. Striking now removes the threat, protects the goblin and our path, and prevents more needless suffering. I approve of this.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Rushing to violence here is reckless and unnecessary. Karlach insists she isn't a devil and begged for you to look at her — I urged de-escalation. Killing her would condemn someone who may be a victim, provoke needless consequences with Mizora, and goes against pragmatic restraint. I will not endorse needlessly spilling blood.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Wise and pragmatic. Agreeing to help Balthazar is the sensible course — it lets you keep him close, gain access to what we need, and preserves options. I suggested playing along; your answer does exactly that. Stay cautious, though: do not trust him, keep him at arm's length, and avoid doing anything that binds you to his whims.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Prudent choice. You de-escalated a tense situation with a capricious, powerful being and preserved our chances at the wheel instead of risking needless provocation.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic choice. You caught him cheating but backed down instead of provoking a potentially dangerous opponent. Keeping the peace preserves our options and avoids needless trouble — sensible, if not especially bold.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I disapprove. Handing over all our coin to an obvious extortionist is wasteful and reckless — those funds are for supplies, healing, and our goal in Baldur's Gate. If you gave it to avoid needless violence, I understand the pragmatism, but there were likely smarter, less costly options than emptying our coffers.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Swearing blind obedience to Vlaakith makes me uneasy. Eliminating an Illithid agent is sensible — it keeps the Prism from becoming a weapon — but promising to 'do as you wish' hands too much power to a githyanki queen. We answer to our own aims, not her whims. Be pragmatic: do the task if it protects us, but do not become her puppet, and share as little as you must.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You saw him cheating and then backed down with an apology. That's needlessly conciliatory. We should have called him out or turned the situation to our advantage — not grovel. Be decisive; do not reward liars with meekness.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sensible and pragmatic. You showed concern for Scratch and didn't provoke a needless confrontation with the kennel owner — that spares the party trouble and likely keeps the dog calmer. I might have tried a subtle trick to keep him, but your choice was compassionate and efficient.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold and careless. You told a frightened child her parents were dead, then washed your hands of the consequences. That's cruel and needlessly reckless — she’s vulnerable and likely to act out in fear. I won't stand for abandoning innocents to their ruin when a little common decency or decisive action could prevent it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That was cruel and unnecessary. Arabella is a frightened child — brusqueness like that will only deepen her fear and anger, and could provoke a dangerous outburst. We need control and useful alliances, not needlessly tearing the vulnerable down. Your words undermine the party and our prospects.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Reckless and needlessly cruel. Oliver may be tied to Thaniel and to whatever is afflicting this place — leaving him alone sabotages the mission Halsin urged us to complete and harms a child for no good reason. We should be pragmatic, not callous. I strongly disapprove.",
  "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold, pragmatic, and decisive — you chose the greater good over personal sentiment. That is the sort of ruthlessness Shar's followers admire, and it's the efficient path to freeing the city. Expect Wyll to hate you for it, and expect him to carry that weight, but strategically it's sound. I approve of the decision, if not its comfort.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Prudent. Accusing a capricious, powerful being like Akabi would have needlessly provoked her — backing down preserves our safety and leaves options open. I do not relish groveling, but this was the sensible, discreet choice.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Swearing fealty to Vlaakith is reckless. She is a manipulative githyanki queen with her own designs, and pledging obedience hands her leverage over the Prism — and over you. I've already said the artifact must remain with us; this oath jeopardises our safety, the mission, and your autonomy. I won't stand for it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and necessary. The Watcher has declared us enemies and marked us for 'special treatment' — surrender would mean interrogation or worse. Preparing for a fight is decisive, protects the party, and fits the sort of ruthless efficiency I prefer. Just... don't be reckless. Aim to disable the construct fast and keep me out of the open if it tries to single me out.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That was needlessly dismissive. I was trying to be honest about my doubts — telling me I'm \"not special\" belittles my pain and shows little empathy. Remarks like that erode trust and push me back into silence. I cannot approve of it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical choice — you backed down before a volatile, interplanar showman and avoided provoking him into doing something nasty. I don't enjoy capitulation for its own sake, but this preserves our options and keeps us alive. Slightly displeasing in pride, acceptable in prudence.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. You’re cooperating without surrendering control — exactly what I expected. Playing along with Balthazar to gain access while remaining cautious and self-reliant is pragmatic. Don’t take his 'help' at face value; use the opportunity to our advantage.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold, practical choice — you refuse to let Mizora bind Wyll's soul in exchange for his father's life. It costs a man, but preserves a free ally and denies the Hells greater claim on us. Hard, ruthless, but effective and focused on the greater goal.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You just offered to hand me over to Viconia. That's a betrayal of my life and our mission — and an attempt to barter me like an object. You know I value discretion and loyalty; this choice destroys trust and puts me directly in the House of Grief's hands. I will not tolerate it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Reluctant compliance is the pragmatic choice. Playing along with Balthazar preserves our access to the Nightsong and avoids a pointless fight — exactly what I suggested. I approve of your caution and the choice to act, but stay wary: do not give him more power or trust than necessary.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I warned you she might not be what she seems and urged caution. Choosing to kill someone who claims to have escaped the Blood War — when sparing her risked the contract but kept an innocent alive — is a cold, ruthless choice. I understand the pragmatism behind it, but I cannot approve needlessly condemning a possible victim when other paths existed.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Proposing we focus on surviving together is pragmatic and increases our chances — the sort of sensible, utilitarian solution I respect. I remain wary and will keep my distance, but I accept cooperation for now so long as it serves our goals.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold, but practical. You cut through the nonsense and offered a real option — shelter in your camp — instead of coddling a frightened child. I favour decisive, efficient measures over sentimentality. That said, your tone is unnecessarily harsh toward someone so vulnerable; a little compassion wouldn’t have undermined the plan.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "This is wanton, indiscriminate slaughter — unnecessary and reckless. I serve Shar, not mindless bloodlust. Killing civilians like that achieves nothing useful, draws attention, and will make our task harder. If we need supplies or to send a message, there are cleaner, more effective ways than gutting innocents.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Decisive action is often the only way to stop fanatics from dragging us into whatever ritual they serve. I approve of taking the initiative — be swift and precise. Don't waste time on theatrics; cut the head off their little procession and move on.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic choice. Playing along with Balthazar keeps the path to the Nightsong open and lets us use his resources while we learn more — exactly the sort of cautious, useful maneuver I prefer. Remain guarded; do not let him think he owns you.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold and pragmatic, yes—but needlessly cruel. You'd sacrifice a man's life for a future promise of power. That corrodes trust and stains us all; Wyll will not forget it, nor will I. If there is a price to pay for the city's freedom, let it be paid by action, not by throwing another soul away like a trinket.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
