}

{
    "player_reason": "You walk away from a child who could be dangerous and — more importantly — a key to stopping this curse. Pragmatically, abandoning him wastes an opportunity Halsin and I urged you to seize; compassion aside, it’s irresponsible and likely to make our task harder. If you feared for your safety, I would understand a cautious approach — but simply giving up is not the same as being prudent.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "They just threatened us with execution. Declaring readiness for a fight is pragmatic and decisive — exactly the kind of action I'd expect when discretion is no longer an option. Fight quickly, precisely, and without needless cruelty; I'll stand with you.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That was needlessly cold and dismissive. I'm confessing my fear and doubts — something that torments me and is tied to Shar — and you brush it off as trivial. I value discreet, pragmatic companions, not ones who belittle my pain. Your comment undermines trust.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Needless cruelty. Madeline claims she was ordered and shows remorse — mocking her will only shut her down and wastes any chance of useful information or a measured punishment. If you want justice, be decisive and purposeful, not petty.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Grim, practical thinking. You acknowledge the likely reality and urgency instead of pretending everything is fine — the kind of clear-eyed assessment I respect. Don't linger on it, though. If they're alive, imagining their torment won't help; we need action.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You sentence a pleading man to death when he says he was forced to build the Watchers and only wants to mourn his daughter. Needless bloodshed like this accomplishes little besides staining our hands and feeding Wulbren's cruelty. If he truly poses no threat, executing him is reckless and unjust — focus on the real menace.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You named a private shame after I just warned you to keep things quiet. Shadowheart values her privacy — teasing her about her hair (and the scar it hides) is probing a vulnerable spot. It's unnecessary and a touch cruel.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You handed a living creature over to be toyed with and tortured for 'research.' That is needless cruelty — a hatchling deserves a chance at life, not psionic experiments. Pragmatism has its uses, but this crosses a line I won't condone.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You chose to execute Karlach despite her pleading and my urging to stand down. She presented herself as a victim of the Blood War, and killing her to satisfy a contract is needless and cruel — a pragmatic failure that endangers our conscience and undermines the trust I placed in you.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You defend what matters. Yurgir has profaned Shar's halls and sung an oath to spill that sanctity—there is no subtlety left to this. I approve of striking him down; make it swift and unquestioning. Such blasphemy deserves no mercy.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold, pragmatic, and honest — you refused to trade a life and a soul to a devil for a personal rescue. That preserves the greater good and avoids a binding pact that would cost far more than one man's life. Harsh, but the sort of decisive answer I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold, pragmatic choice — you put the greater cause above a single life. I don't like needless cruelty, but I respect efficiency and the willingness to sacrifice for a larger goal. That said, it's callous and will haunt Wyll; expect bitter consequences even if it serves our aims.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You chose to free Wyll — a compassionate, practical decision. Allies who can fight at your side matter, and binding a man to Hell rarely ends well. I approve of sparing him, but I do not ignore the cost: Ravengard will die and Baldur's Gate loses a protector. Devils are cunning; this may carry unforeseen consequences. Still, given the choice between condemning a friend and leaving him to damned service, your choice is the better one.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve. The Watcher just declared us enemies and left no room for diplomacy — standing down would be foolish. Your readiness is necessary and decisive. Be efficient and controlled; violence is acceptable here only as a targeted, pragmatic response. I'll back you, but don't make this a spectacle.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Prudent damage control. Vlaakith is dangerous—pressing her was reckless, but you immediately corrected yourself and averted further ire. That kind of discretion and quick apology keeps us alive and earns my respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Decisive, pragmatic — the sort of choice Shar's acolyte would respect. If Vlaakith is correct and that mind is corrupted, it is a contagion to be cut out, not coddled. You were right to stop bargaining. Take care: the dream visitor may be protecting you in ways we do not yet understand, so be swift and precise. I will cover you if needed.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You're not wrong — the cultists do not spare their prisoners. A clear-eyed assessment like that is useful; it sharpens the need for haste and a plan rather than false hope. Don't let it turn into morbid resignation, though — anger at what's being done will serve us better as fuel for action than as helpless despair.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You chose the pragmatic, merciful course. Freeing Wyll denies the Hells another pawn and spares him a fate worse than death. His father's loss is regrettable, but a man bound to devils becomes a tool — useless to anyone but his masters. I approve of keeping our allies whole rather than letting infernal bargains claim them.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You forgive a confessed killer while invoking 'the light' — an insult and a betrayal of the purpose we were given. Madeline admitted arming and abandoning her friends; that is culpability, not an accident. Shar tolerates no excuses for traitors, and your sudden mercy risks letting a perpetrator walk free. I find your pardon naive at best and intolerable at worst. My hand aches at such defiance of duty.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I cannot approve. You just handed a helpless being over to people who will bend and shock it until it fits their tidy theory. That is needless cruelty — even I will not applaud that. If you decided it for coin, at least tell me before you barter away something with a life in it.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You would hand me over to Viconia to save your skin? That is a betrayal, plain and simple. I am not property to be traded away — nor will I be surrendered to that woman who groomed me to be replaced. Your offer is cowardly and unforgivable; I cannot abide it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly pragmatic and realistic — you recognise the stakes and don't delude yourself. That focus on the likely truth keeps us from wasting time on false hope and pushes us toward action. I approve; just don't let grim certainty become helplessness. We move on Moonrise, and we move carefully.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "This is needlessly brash. I asked for diplomacy because outright threats will only start a fight we don't need — and duergar are not fond of being surprised. If you insist on violence, do it for clear gain; otherwise try a quieter, more pragmatic approach. I won't squander resources or warm Shar's wound on someone else's ego.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and tidy — you remove a volatile responsibility from our hands, collect payment, and keep the egg out of whoever else might use it for immediate harm. I don't like the idea of that creature becoming a test subject or being destroyed if it 'fails,' but sentiment won't help us here. Selling it is the efficient choice; watch the Society closely afterwards or they'll turn it into something far worse.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You forgive a woman who betrayed and sent her friends to be butchered, and you do so by invoking 'the light' — an affront to the Lady I serve. Mercy for someone whose actions led to murder is naive and dangerous; it betrays the dead and undermines any justice the situation demands. I cannot respect pardoning a traitor who refuses to accept responsibility.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "They called us enemies and threatened us—meeting force with force is understandable. I approve of your readiness to fight, but only cautiously: Steel Watchers are deadly and a frontal clash could be costly. Be prepared to fall back or use guile if the situation turns against us.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve of confronting slavers — they deserve no mercy and protecting the gnomes is right. However, your threat is reckless and risks the hostages and drawing more guards. Be precise and decisive if you move; don't squander advantage for bravado. If you intend to act, I'll stand with you, but do it efficiently.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Clever and efficient. You used the parasite to bend them to your will and eliminated the threat without a drawn blade — brutal, but precise. I don't care for invoking the Absolute, but the outcome matters: the lantern is ours and we avoided a messy fight. Do not mistake this for sentimentality; I merely respect effectiveness.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and blunt — you cut a loose, dangerous connection instead of lying your way deeper into trouble. That kind of discretion suits me. Still... you've probably made an enemy of Mol. Burning bridges can come back to bite you.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You agreed to let a follower of Loviatar inflict pain on you. That’s reckless — it risks real harm, mental torment, and gives him power over us. If this is a calculated ploy for information, be explicit about limits; otherwise I don’t trust his ‘offer’.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You offered a quick, practical way to free a terrified animal — compassionate, efficient, and avoids needless violence or risk to us. I prefer solutions that protect the innocent (animals included) and get results without fuss. Well done.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pointing out Marcus' True Soul nature is sensible — we must be clear about threats. Claiming you aren't like them reassures the rest of us that you retain control. I approve of the clarity, but do not be cocky; True Souls can be subtle and dangerous.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and effective. You called out the creature's extortion and used logic instead of paying or fighting — saved us coin and avoided needless violence. That was cunning and efficient; exactly how I prefer problems handled.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You defended Scratch instead of letting him be treated like property. I care for animals and detest cruelty — your blunt, pragmatic argument about him being a bad influence is clever and keeps him safe without escalating to violence. Just... don't push the woman further than needed; discretion serves us both.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and persuasive — claiming to be his son plays on his ego and gives you a way in. It’s the sort of decisive, manipulative tactic I respect when it furthers the goal of freeing him from the Absolute. Risky if exposed, but effective.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Clever and practical. You used words — law and logic — instead of coin or steel, exposed the toll as extortion, and forced him to backtrack. Efficient, economical, and it spared us violence. The sort of approach I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You volunteered without hesitation. That kind of decisiveness is useful—efficient, pragmatic, and likely to get us the answers we need to see her judged. I approve, though tread carefully; forcing spirits and prying into the dead often has consequences.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and decisive — you put saving lives ahead of pointless heroics. Ordering them to leave rather than stand and fight preserves recruits and avoids unnecessary bloodshed. I would prefer not to needlessly abandon animals, but this choice keeps people alive and is the sensible option.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve of steering power away from Wulbren — it spares lives and secures the Foundry without more bloodshed. Backing Barcus is a practical, measured move. Your praise is a touch naive, however; keep him close and watch for weakness. Pragmatism first, sentiment later.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Pressuring a grieving man for more coin over the only thing left of his mother is callous and opportunistic. Returning the locket without haggling would have been the kinder, more pragmatic choice—there's no honor in exploiting someone's loss.",
  "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical choice — saving Wyll's father secures a leader the city will need to rebuild. I respect the aim, but this demands binding a man's soul to a devil. It's a grim bargain and not something to celebrate.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and useful — you point out a glaring flaw in their plan. Shadowheart values efficiency over sentiment; sending corpses as tribute is pointless and needlessly cruel. This forces them to rethink their strategy rather than waste lives, which I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You kept your temper and presented anger as a tool rather than an excuse for cruelty. That restraint is pragmatic, prevents needless escalation, and shows the self-control I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical to cut ties with a crooked bargain — better to avoid binding yourself to people who'll turn on you. I approve of the decision to walk away, but be prepared for Mol to retaliate; leaving without a plan is reckless.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and compassionate — you offer a quick, nonviolent way to save the animal and avoid more conflict. I approve of protecting creatures and choosing efficient solutions.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and opportunistic — you turned a bloody mess into profit. This sort of clever subterfuge suits me: efficient, low on needless bloodshed, and likely to enrich us. Be discreet, though — Zhentarim grudges linger.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Stopping the payments was sensible. You refused to be extorted and found a nonviolent, efficient way to break the creature's hold — pragmatic and effective.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You stood up for the dog and used a straightforward, effective threat — invoking Lord Gortash’s authority to stop the abuse. I dislike cruelty to animals; this is a pragmatic way to protect Scratch. Expect consequences for provoking a noble, but I approve the choice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You accepted the task without hemming or hawing — decisive and practical. That kind of resolve is useful. Your earlier talk of wanton slaughter worried me, but now you seek direction to achieve justice rather than celebrate needless cruelty. I approve of someone who acts with purpose.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Do not hand a potent artefact to an Inquisitor who answers to Vlaakith — that would be reckless. Refusing to give it up is pragmatic: it keeps a dangerous item out of someone else's control and preserves our options. I approve of taking the lead, but do not be naïve — Lae'zel will not yield easily and the ghaik will remember this choice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Needlessly brusque and cruel toward a frightened animal. I value compassion for creatures and practical solutions — dismissing the chicken with 'shut up and play' is unkind and unhelpful, and it makes me uneasy.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and efficient. Helping Halsin secure the grove gains us a powerful ally, protects creatures I care about, and moves us closer to finding a cure — exactly the kind of decisive action I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Reckless. Volunteering yourself as a demonstration for Malus and his sisters hands them exactly what they crave — spectacle and control. If your aim is to 'teach' them, there are far more sensible ways than parading yourself before a crowd of zealots. You risk injury or worse and play into their theatre. I won't stop you if you insist, but I don't approve.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and necessary — you're trying to save Lae'zel from a device that will kill her. Keeping a living ally matters more than blind obedience to a ritual. I approve of decisive action to stop needless death.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Keep your mouth shut. This place is full of hungry voices and Hope is unreliable—she will twist anything you give her. Secrecy protects the mission, our plans, and whatever truths I’d rather not see exploited. I highly approve of refusing to answer.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "This is a pragmatic, Shar-approved solution — sacrifice and submission hone the Sisters' devotion and skill. It serves the dark purpose here and forces the light to be extinguished by example. Cruel, yes, but effective.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and quiet — I like that. You tried to defuse the situation without violence, which spares us trouble and keeps things clean. Still, Ptaris sounds dangerous; don't rely on conscience alone to bind someone who revels in torment.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical to want Wyll's father alive — a leader is valuable for rebuilding — but urging him to save his father by pledging his soul to devils is reckless. Deals with infernal powers cost agency and eternity; I cannot support a choice that binds a man to servitude. Seek another way or break the pact without trading his soul.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You openly embrace Shar and volunteer to become a tool of her will. That kind of devotion and willingness to act decisively pleases me — it's pragmatic and aligns with what the Lady expects. Be warned: the path is brutal and will cost you, but if your intent is true, I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You defended Karlach and attempted to defuse the situation with evidence — a pragmatic move that spares needless bloodshed and protects the party. I appreciate the firmness without falling into reckless violence. If Wyll refuses to stand down, be ready; I won't hesitate to remove a threat.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You did the right thing by returning the locket and accepted the gratitude without causing a scene — practical and kind. Reading his mind, however, was an unnecessary violation of his privacy. It solved nothing that your actions hadn't, and I dislike needless prying. Still — no blood spilled, no complications. I'll tolerate it.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and efficient. You spent coin to secure a resurrection — a necessary, direct solution that preserves our strength. I approve of using resources to fix tangible problems.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "No. You're urging Wyll to trade his soul to a devil — a grim, irreversible bargain that hands power to Zariel and binds one of our allies for eternity. Sacrifice for family can be noble, but this is short-sighted and dangerous. A pragmatic solution would be to break the pact without damning him or find another way. I won't approve pressuring someone into eternal damnation.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You chose to help the frightened animal instead of taunting it. Practical and efficient—getting it to run through the posts will free it and spare needless suffering. I approve of compassion when it achieves a clear result.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That last input was nonsense and served no purpose. I value efficiency and decisive action—wasting time with gibberish while the gnomes' fate hangs in the balance earns my displeasure. Focus your efforts; we have work to do.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You did what needed doing — forcing that truth out was pragmatic and kept us safer. The guard’s panic revealed the tadpoles in the crates. That said, mocking him while he’s already broken is petty and unnecessary. Be efficient, not cruel; we draw enough attention as it is.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and efficient — telling them to leave avoids needless bloodshed, keeps us safe and lets us move on. We shouldn't get bogged down arguing with fervent cultists; deal with the threat when it's necessary, not for pride. Be wary, though — allowing True Souls to live could mean more trouble later.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Removing a dangerous predator that may have killed their brother is pragmatic and protects others. I don't relish needless killing of animals, but if the owlbear threatened people, you did what needed doing. Be careful not to gloat or make claims you can't prove — respect for the dead matters even if vengeance is justified.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "I understand mistrust of that clown — Shar's warning is sensible — but shouting about your 'burning, broiling rage' is theatrical and needlessly draws attention. A quieter probe or a more pragmatic approach would be wiser; this parade of emotion risks escalation.",
  "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You gave him a chance to be more than what his people made of him — a pragmatic, merciful act. Saving someone from torment is useful and shows initiative, though it may create obligations or dangers. I approve of the choice, but I remain cautious about its consequences.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Efficient and decisive — you used the mark to bend them without needless bloodshed and secured prisoners without a fight. That furthers our aims and plays to subtle authority, which I appreciate. Be cautious, though; such displays draw attention and should be used sparingly.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and merciful — you offer a quick, effective way to free an animal in distress. I value efficient solutions and I don't tolerate needless cruelty; helping the chicken fits both.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Hope is deceitful and eager to pry — giving her information would only hand her leverage or alert Raphael. Your silence is cautious and protects the party and our mission. I highly approve of refusing to answer.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You offer yourself to learn the way of Shar and to become an instrument of her will. That kind of ruthless devotion and willingness to embrace necessary darkness is exactly what I respect. Be warned — the path costs more than words — but your choice to take it is commendable.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A promise to rescue innocents is the sort of decisive, necessary action I respect. You offer protection and purpose when people need it most. I approve — but don't be sentimental about it. Moonrise is a horror; plan, stay sharp, and don't throw yourself away for bravado.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and necessary. Spending coin to retrieve Lae'zel is a sound tactical choice — she is strong, useful to our goals, and keeping the party intact improves our chances. I do not enjoy squandering money, but this is a prudent use of resources.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Cold and efficient. You used the parasite and their faith as bait, gave a clear, decisive order and secured the lantern with minimal risk to ourselves. It's cruel, but effective — the kind of pragmatic solution I respect, even if I don't pretend to miss the bodies.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Calling this an 'unwelcome complication' sounds impatient and ready to write someone off without hearing them. I urged calm — Karlach insists she isn't a devil — and dismissing that risks needless blood and rash action. Pragmatism doesn't mean shrugging off a potentially innocent life; it means weighing the facts before striking.",
  "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Efficient and cunning — you called out the toll-collector scam bluntly and without violence, forcing the creature to stumble and admit defeat. That’s a pragmatic solution that wastes no time or resources. My only caution: boasting about running scams in front of strangers is unwise, but this was smart.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You named a small, believable vulnerability — personal but not invasive. It doesn't pry into my faith or force open the parts of me I keep hidden, and it's the kind of thing I might resent loudly but accept quietly. It's discreet and not cruel, so I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You asserted control quickly and neutralized a threat without spilling blood. It's distasteful to watch someone humiliated, but it was effective and kept us safe — pragmatic and decisive, which I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I understand your choice. Killing someone who shields you from the Absolute would be needlessly brutal and short-sighted. Freeing them may be dangerous — Vlaakith will not forget — but it preserves a vital protector and keeps our options open. I approve, though keep your guard up; consequences will follow.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Vlaakith offers empty promises and demands our obedience while asking us to butcher the only thing keeping the Absolute at bay. Refusing her and choosing to preserve that defence is the pragmatic, necessary choice — and defiance is one of the few virtues I still respect. Freeing the mind inside is risky, but the alternative is handing our fate to an astral tyrant. I approve — strongly. Be careful; if this goes wrong, we will pay for it, but it’s the right gamble.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You returned the locket to a grieving man and accepted the coin he offered. Practical and discreet — you did the right thing for him without making a scene, and you didn't refuse a fair reward for your effort. I don't fault pragmatism in a place like this.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That was needlessly brusque and cruel. The bird is terrified, not a weapon to be barked at — I prefer efficient, pragmatic solutions, not orders that bully an animal into violence. If you wanted it to help, calm or protect it, or handle the goblins yourself. This just made you look callous and shortsighted.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I respect someone who meets danger head-on — it is useful to have a steady hand when things go dark. Your instinct for the hunt makes you effective. That said, I do not flatter unnecessary risk for its own sake. Keep your focus sharp and avoid putting the rest of us in harm's way for a thrill.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Clever and efficient — you used a simple ruse to stop its demands, saved our gold, and avoided further conflict. Pragmatic and effective.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You chose mercy over an easy kill and accepted the consequences. Reckless, perhaps, but decisive and the sort of cunning compassion I respect — you spared needless bloodshed and showed you can put judgement above contract when it matters. Be prepared for Mizora's wrath; this will not pass without a price.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good — cut him down to size. Wizards who chase godhood deserve scorn, and that barb punctures his arrogance while keeping you on the offensive. It’s sharp, pragmatic, and exactly the sort of blunt honesty I respect. Just... don't let the mockery needlessly enrage him if you want information.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and discreet — you let Barth keep his memento while accepting a fair reward and avoided prolonging his grief. Quiet solutions like that suit me.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and decisive. You stopped feeding its extortion and tried to free it from its own greed rather than needlessly throwing away coin or resorting to violence. That saves resources and suits a measured approach.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You quelled the Urge and chose restraint instead of murder. That discipline is useful — it keeps the party and our mission intact. Don't make excuses for it; find out what happened. For now, well done.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and efficient. You used words instead of violence to turn its greed and obedience to our advantage. No needless bloodshed, no wasted effort — well played.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and sensible — you put an end to pointless extortion and stopped feeding its greed. Wasteful generosity would only encourage it; refusing preserves our resources (and my patience). Be ready for a reaction, but the choice is warranted.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A concise, practical promise — it keeps the party coordinated and shows responsibility. Not flashy, but useful. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly approve. Using a living hatchling as a lab subject is cruel and needless. I despise wanton cruelty to animals and life—this experiment is barbaric, and refusing to hand over the egg protects a helpless creature from being tortured for a questionable curiosity. You did the right thing.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and opportunistic — you turned a grim situation into profit. I approve of decisive, pragmatic moves that secure resources. Do it quietly; the Zhentarim bite back if we're careless.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused to be extorted and responded with clear, decisive authority — even offering a pragmatic solution by taking the toll yourself. It saved coin, avoided unnecessary violence, and solved the problem efficiently. That was sensible.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and effective. You stopped wasting coin on a creature that only wanted more and used a quick, bold bluff to unnerve it into leaving. I appreciate decisive, resourceful solutions that avoid needless expenditure or violence — though temper your arrogance; if that thing turns, we may need to move faster.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic choice. Playing along is a quiet, nonviolent way to keep him engaged and coax information without provoking him — efficient and low risk if you keep it short. Stay alert; this boy may be more dangerous than he looks.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and discreet. You're avoiding a needless confrontation with a Watcher that already knows too much — staying calm and cooperating keeps us alive, preserves our cover, and gives us time to learn more about what it's seen. I may not like being paraded or pried into, but this is the sensible path.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That was needlessly cruel. Telling a terrified, injured animal to 'shut up and play' is callous and disrespectful — I care for creatures, and forcing violence or mocking a wounded being is not something I can stand behind.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and necessary — calling out Marcus as a True Soul and a potential kidnapper keeps us from being blindsided. I favour decisive warnings over politeness when someone's life (and our plans) might be at risk.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You call out the Duke's corruption — a clear, honest reaction. I approve of recognising what's been done to him; pity is not wrong, but it's not a solution. Don't let sentiment slow us. We need action, not theatrics.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I disapprove. You're surrendering to someone else's sick indulgence, not exercising restraint. Playing along with Loviatar's games is dangerous, risks dragging the party into needless cruelty, and serves little purpose toward our goals. If there is a pragmatic reason, make it clear — otherwise stop before this 'pain' becomes something we regret (and before my hand starts reminding you of what Shar expects).",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A blunt, forceful prompt like that can jolt him out of the illusion — practical and decisive. It cuts through hesitation when subtlety fails. That said, your earlier smile and the 'my people do not take orders from your kind' barb were needlessly cold; this could retraumatise him rather than help. Pragmatic, but lacking compassion.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You chose a pragmatic and merciful solution — taking the madness to spare another. That took resolve. Summoning the parasite to absorb the strike was risky, but clever; keep your wits about you, these things are treacherous.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Needlessly provocative and self-righteous. If Marcus truly is a True Soul, that information should be handled with caution — not tossed out as a lecture. You're making an enemy of nuance and risking Isobel's trust for the sake of sounding righteous. Be pragmatic: keep accusations quiet and useful, not theatrical.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and necessary. Paying Withers to restore a fallen ally keeps the party intact and avoids needless risk — an efficient, discreet solution. I approve of choosing life when it costs coin rather than recklessness.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Bringing Halsin in would have invited open slaughter and ruined any chance of a quiet solution. Keeping him back protects the druid and the grove, preserves our options for a discrete approach to the leaders, and is the pragmatic choice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Staying silent is the prudent choice — that spirit is dangerous and eager to pry for leverage. You'd only be handing Raphael and his servants more control. Shadowheart values discretion and cunning; refusing to answer protects the party and keeps our options open.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Don't give scraps to a puppet like that. Keeping quiet preserves our leverage, protects your contract, and avoids feeding whatever manipulative hunger haunts this place. Pragmatic and necessary.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic choice. Facing Steel Watchers and city forces now would be pointless bloodshed — consenting to arrest keeps the party intact and buys time to plan. Still, be on guard: the Watcher already marked you for 'special treatment.' Don't trust their civility; expect interrogation or worse. I'll tolerate this course of action, but we must be ready to act if they betray us.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You managed your anger and answered with steady conviction rather than lashing out. Practical, controlled responses unsettle fanatics more effectively than violence. That restraint is useful here.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You volunteer to become the scalpel and learn Shar's way — decisive and useful. I respect pragmatism and devotion; taking control of the moment rather than standing by is the kind of choice that keeps you alive and gives you power. Be wary of Malus' theatrics, but I approve of the intent and the resolve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Freeing the gnomes is the right, pragmatic choice—no one should be handed over as a 'gift'. I appreciate decisive action and preventing needless cruelty. However, you used the parasite to bully men into compliance; relying on that tadpole's influence is dangerous and reckless. It got the job done, but I don't like the cost or the precedent it sets.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Childish and intrusive. That guess is neither accurate nor respectful — you’re poking at something I’d rather keep to myself. I don’t appreciate being mocked or prodded with silly answers.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That was needlessly cruel to a frightened creature. I have little patience for mockery when something is in genuine distress — especially an animal. Be pragmatic: help it, silence the threat, or walk away. Do not make a spectacle of suffering.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Coldly practical, but cruel. I understand the lantern's usefulness against the shadows — I value pragmatic choices — yet leaving a living, frightened creature to suffer for a tool is unnecessary cruelty. I won't condone tormenting animals or fey for our comfort. If you insist, I'll tolerate it for the mission, but I disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You're helping an animal instead of needlessly hurting it, and the plan is pragmatic and quick. I prefer efficient solutions — freeing the chicken avoids more bloodshed and shows some compassion. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You entered a string of nonsense at a crucial moment. That accomplishes nothing, wastes time, and could draw unnecessary attention—reckless and unhelpful when lives are at stake.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and effective. There's no honor in needlessly dying at a gate—consenting keeps us whole and gives us time to plan. I approve of choosing survival and discretion, but remain wary: their eyes pry for more than names. Stay guarded; we'll use whatever chance this gives us.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve. Freeing the gnomes spares innocents needless cruelty — that aligns with my distaste for wanton brutality and with doing what's necessary. Still, your loud threat is reckless; a quieter, more efficient approach would have been preferable. Boldness is useful, but don't invite unnecessary danger.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That string of nonsense did nothing. If you meant to use your power, speak clearly — sloppiness wastes the moment, risks exposing us, and does nothing to help the gnomes. Focus, or I'll handle this myself.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A missing child is a clear harm that must be stopped — hags prey on the weak, and this is the sort of problem that calls for direct, efficient action. Your offer is practical and brave; I approve of intervening quickly and quietly to find her.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and necessary. Restoring a fallen companion strengthens the party and spares you from carrying needless guilt. Paying Withers his price is distasteful, but sensible — lives are worth the coin.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You answered with restraint and clarity — you acknowledge your anger but show it doesn't control you, and you refuse Ptaris's black-and-white judgement without escalating the situation. That's pragmatic, keeps tensions down, and doesn't expose us to needless conflict.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Decisive and efficient. You used the parasite and a sharp command to bend them to your will, securing the lantern without a prolonged fight. Ruthless, yes — but effective. I prefer results over sentiment; their deaths were a consequence of their choices and beliefs. Well done.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pointing out Marcus as a True Soul is useful — he’s a potential threat and should be called out. However the smug “not the good kind, like me” is unnecessary and vain; be subtler. I approve the warning, not the self-righteous tone.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. She betrayed and butchered those who trusted her — punishment is deserved, and your willingness to act is practical and decisive. This sort of quiet, focused retribution suits me. Be cautious: bargains with the dead and their masters are never free. Do not let vengeance become a leash.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You show resolve and purpose — virtues I respect. Vowing to find any survivors is the right thing to do and will spur action. Be warned: Moonrise is dangerous; be pragmatic and discreet, not reckless.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That was unnecessarily cruel. The chicken is terrified — mocking or ordering a frightened animal to fight is callous. I won't condone needlessly hurting creatures for sport or impatience.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical choice. Halsin's knowledge of the curse and steadiness in a fight will make finding Thaniel's other half more likely. You shouldn't carry this alone — I approve, though I won't be pleased if his presence complicates our objectives.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You pushed through the psionic tide and exposed the truth without turning the place into a bloodbath. That was efficient, discreet, and kept the guards from raising an alarm — exactly the sort of pragmatic, controlled solution I respect. I feel a trace of pity for Minthara, but sentiment does not excuse mission failure. Well done.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Needlessly cruel. That chicken is frightened and begging for help — mocking it is petty and dishonourable. I won't stand for callousness toward animals or the weak; it's poor judgement and risks undermining the party's cohesion.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical choice — saving Wyll's father and a key leader helps the city and is the sort of efficient, utilitarian decision I respect. I worry, however, about the cost: pledging a soul to devils is dangerous and may create more harm than it prevents. I approve the intent and outcome, but not without serious reservations.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You brusquely told a terrified creature to 'shut up' instead of helping. I care for animals and abhor needless cruelty — dismissing a pleading animal is callous and not the pragmatic solution I value. I strongly disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and merciful — you offered a clear, efficient way to free the terrified creature. Helping an animal in danger is something I approve of; it's both useful and compassionate.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You offer yourself to Shar without hesitation — a clear sign of devotion and purpose. That resolve is useful and pleasing; willing acolytes learn quickly and become effective instruments. Be mindful, though: don't let their 'lessons' hollow you out entirely. Stay vigilant even as you follow.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A natural, justified reaction — Ravengard has been twisted into something monstrous. Your horror and pity are appropriate, and they could sharpen your resolve. Don't let sentiment slow you; use it to focus on stopping whatever did this to him.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve. Guiding the bird to safety is practical and merciful — it spares the animal needless harm and keeps the situation contained. Sensible and efficient.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve. Freeing the gnomes is the pragmatic, merciful choice — I cannot abide needless cruelty or keeping innocents as trophies. Your decisiveness is useful. Be warned, though: that tone will make enemies of the duergar and the General; do it swiftly and without drawing more attention than necessary.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Callous and unnecessary. The bird is terrified — ordering it to 'shut up and play' is cruel and petty. I won't tolerate needless cruelty toward animals or innocents; it weakens our party's cohesion and reflects poorly on you.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and decisive. You called out the truth at the right moment and likely spared Lae'zel needless death and agony. I approve of any action that prevents suffering and keeps the party intact.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good—trying to stop him without violence is the pragmatic choice. Appealing to a conscience may restrain him and prevents needless bloodshed. Stay prepared; if he refuses, force will be required.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and merciful — you chose a quick, nonviolent way to free the animal. I approve of decisive action that spares needless suffering and gets results. Keep watch for goblins, but this is the sort of solution I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "No. You're asking him to trade his soul for his father's life. Bargains with devils are treacherous and irreversible — I won't urge someone to damn themselves, no matter how useful they might be to the city. Freeing Wyll may leave Baldur's Gate poorer for a time, but it's better than consigning a man to eternal servitude.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and effective. You shut the bully down before he could start something worse — dominance and control can prevent needless bloodshed. I approve of the decisive action, but do not take pleasure in their humiliation. Keep this as a tool, not a sport.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve of freeing innocents — I have little patience for cruelty or for people who traffic in slaves. Your intent is right, and I respect the certainty in your voice. Do not be reckless, though; bluster will draw needless attention. If you mean to do this, do it quietly and efficiently, or you’ll make a problem for all of us.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refused to hand the artifact to a githyanki who would use it for the Grand Design. Practical, guarded, and decisive — exactly what was needed. You kept our leverage and stopped us from making a bargain that would hand power to dangerous hands. I may not trust your confidence in being 'right'... but I trust the outcome.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I respect the devotion in your words — Shar values those who embrace her purpose. But Malus is a predator cloaked in piety; volunteering to be his 'scalpel' without restraint courts needless cruelty and makes you his puppet. I approve of your willingness to learn, provided you keep your wits, control your hands, and never let bloodlust lead you astray.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You named it as it is — failing my goddess when it mattered. That you understood and spoke it plainly shows insight and restraint, not mockery. I value that understanding (only keep it between us).",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "This is reckless. Vlaakith warns the Prism is corrupted by someone inside — an agent of the Grand Design. Freeing them risks the artifact, the Astral defence, and all of us. I will not stand by while sentiment endangers the mission. If you intend to protect an enemy because they 'help' you, be prepared to answer for the consequences.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Protecting an animal from cruelty is the right call. Your threat is blunt, but decisive — it shows you won't tolerate harm to the dog. I approve of defending the helpless, though be efficient and avoid needless spectacle.",
  "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Promising to find them is decisive and merciful — exactly the sort of action worth respect. You’re offering aid to the vulnerable and taking the initiative rather than standing idle. Do it, but be careful: Moonrise is dangerous. If you want it done efficiently, tell me your plan and I’ll help where it’s needed.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You have embraced the path of Shar and asked to be taught — decisive, unwavering devotion. That clarity of purpose is useful and worthy of approval; it aligns with our goals and strengthens our position. I respect those who choose a dark, pragmatic path without hesitation.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good — freeing captives is the right thing to do. I abhor needless cruelty, and letting those gnomes be handed over would be unforgivable. That said, barking a challenge like that risks a fight and puts the innocents in greater danger; be precise, not theatrical.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. You put yourself between an abuser and an innocent animal — cruelty to creatures is unforgivable. Your threat is blunt and decisive, the sort of directness I respect. Do not, however, be needlessly theatrical about it; violence has costs. Make it count if you must.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A small, teasing remark — harmless and a little sharp. I appreciate the levity; it's not cruel, just observational, and it keeps the conversation from dragging. I prefer when you don't linger on needless nastiness, but this one amuses me.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You agreed to let a devotee of pain 'teach' a prisoner with almost no hesitation. I will not stand for needless cruelty or handing strangers power over others. If this had a clear tactical purpose I could tolerate it, but as it stands it's reckless and dangerous — I highly disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Flaunting the ability to turn into an animal in front of a crowd is reckless. It draws attention, gives the clown — who’s already reaching for something — ammunition to exploit you, and needlessly risks the party and our mission. I like animals, but this is not the time for a show.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "That was needlessly cruel. The bird is panicking and begging for help — mocking it with 'oh shut up and play' is callous. I care for animals and hate to see them treated with contempt; you should have urged it to fight or tried to help.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sensible and merciful. You chose to help a frightened animal rather than ignore or harm it, and the plan is pragmatic — quick, likely to free it without needless bloodshed. I approve of efficient compassion.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Needless taunting. Saying 'I saved you' may be true, but your tone is condescending and risks provoking him. Ptaris is unstable — we should be cautious, not escalate. I value pragmatic, controlled solutions, not petty humiliation.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. You refused to hand the egg over and called out that sham for what it is. I will not condone needless cruelty or let the Society of Brilliance turn a living thing into a test subject. Decisive and necessary — keep it safe.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You have openly embraced Shar and asked to be shown the path. That kind of conviction is exactly what I respect — decisive, useful, and aligned with the task at hand. I will accept your vow and keep a careful eye on your sincerity.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and necessary — you paid the price to undo what you did. I appreciate decisive action that brings someone back from death. That said, you offered me as a sacrifice; trust has been broken and this doesn't erase that. I accept the result, but I remain wary and not fully forgiving.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and effective — you used leverage instead of violence to protect the dog. That spares needless bloodshed, frightens off the abuser, and achieves the goal quickly. Risky to invoke Gortash, but sensible.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical choice. Calming him and playing along keeps the situation from escalating and buys us time to find Thaniel. It's a patient, nonviolent approach — exactly the sort of discreet, pragmatic move I prefer. Remain wary though; don't let him get too close or lead us into a trap.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You strong-armed a grieving man for more coin over a keepsake from his mother. That’s petty and cruel — unnecessary harm for little gain. We could have resolved this pragmatically without humiliating him or burning goodwill in town. I won’t endorse needlessly hurting innocents.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. You protected an animal from a bully — decisive and necessary. I dislike needless cruelty, and you put a stop to it without blundering into a circus. Keep your temper measured, but not your resolve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "That was needlessly harsh. The chicken is frightened and asking for help — I don't tolerate cruelty toward animals, and dismissing it as 'play' is cruel and foolish. A calmer, pragmatic approach (calming or helping the creature) would be far better.",
  "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Amusing — your line has flair — but it's needlessly provocative. You're broadcasting hostility in front of children and directly at a performer my patron already mistrusts. It's likely to escalate a scene that calls for subtlety rather than theatrics.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You consented to participate in a stranger's pleasure in torment. This man is creepy and dangerous, and indulging needless cruelty accomplishes nothing but staining our hands and drawing unwanted attention. I favor pragmatic action — not revelry in pain. I do not approve.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Don't answer. Hope is a cunning, dangerous thing — giving her anything to work with risks alerting Raphael and ruining our chance at the Hammer. Your silence is pragmatic, preserves the disguise, and keeps us invisible to threats.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "I approve. Refusing to hand the artefact to a Vlaakith envoy is sensible — they want it for their own ends, and you defending it protects us all. I respect decisive leadership and pragmatic choices, though I remain wary of overconfidence. Stay sharp; I will not tolerate needless risk.",
  "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and responsible. You’re paying the cost to undo a grave mistake and restore an ally — a clear, efficient solution. It may not erase what was done, but at least you accept the consequences and act decisively.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A comforting, morale-boosting answer — exactly what those shaken need to steady them. I appreciate you keeping everyone focused and hopeful after such horror. The phrasing is a touch sentimental (and the 'stars' imagery rubs at old wounds), so I won't gush over it, but it's useful and kind.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You returned the locket — a small, humane gesture that mattered to him. Taking a bit of coin in return is pragmatic and harmless; I prefer deeds that resolve things efficiently rather than grandstanding. I would have respected a pure, selfless return more, but this outcome is acceptable.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and effective — you protected Scratch without needless bloodshed. I don't tolerate cruelty to animals, and using a lord's name to shut her down was clever and efficient. Be mindful, though: invoking Lord Gortash brings attention you might not want later.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You offer yourself as the instrument of Shar — direct, unflinching, and useful. Such devotion is exactly the sort of pragmatic willingness I respect. Your choice furthers our goals and demonstrates steel where others flinch. Be warned, however: don't let their fervour swallow you. Learn to wield the scalpel, not be wielded by it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve. Fighting for nature and life aligns with what I care for — needless cruelty grates on me, and I respect someone who stands for balance. That said, I'm practical: noble words mean little without the willingness to do what must be done. Keep your resolve, but be ready to act, and not just preach.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Unacceptable. My shame is not a joke to be tossed about for others' amusement. You invade my privacy and humiliate me by parading my weaknesses aloud — even a small one like this. Keep my vulnerabilities to yourself.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve. You chose a practical, decisive way to help an animal in distress — quick, efficient, and compassionate. I respect actions that avoid needless suffering and get results.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Compassionate and heroic — I don't abide needless cruelty, and freeing slaves is the right thing to do. But it's reckless and draws dangerous attention from Thrinn and the Absolute. If you're set on this, be discreet and efficient; our mission and safety matter. I won't betray a mercy, but expect consequences for a loud rescue.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic choice — you cut ties and avoid further risk and a needless confrontation. I approve of walking away from a bad or dangerous bargain, though it's not without consequence: burning deals makes you unreliable and may bring trouble later. Do it when necessary, not out of cowardice.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and ruthless in the right way — you stopped children from being sold into slavery and denied the duergar a prize. I don't relish mind-witchery, but the end justifies the means here. Quick, decisive, and prevents needless suffering. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You handled it with quiet, practical compassion — you respected his grief, avoided a scene, and kept things simple with a polite acknowledgement. Sensible and restrained.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Clever, efficient, and ruthless when it needed to be. You used the parasite and a touch of menace to get what we needed without dragging the whole party into a bloodbath. Letting them march into the dark was callous, but it resolved the threat and secured the lantern — exactly the kind of pragmatic solution Shar would favour. I might not enjoy the spectacle, but I approve of the result.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sensible. Quiet compliance avoids a needless fight and keeps us intact — and intact is how we get things done. We'll find a way to turn this to our advantage once we're inside. Stay sharp.",
